Reverse osmosis is a pressure dependent process. The higher the quantity of stuff dissolved into water the higher the pressure required by the process.
 Seawater can be made into very good drinking water at between 800 and 1,000 pounds of pressure per square inch. 
City water processes readily at forty pounds per square inch.
 Three main types of reverse osmosis systems are TW for tap water ( tape wrapped membrane )
BW brackish water systems bad well water ,salt water intrusion , extreme dissolved mineral contact or water from river water mixed with seawater. BW systems typically operate at 400- 600 pounds per square inch
 SW seawater systems , these systems operate between 800 and 1,000 psi and process seawater .
 Seawater is considered to be about 3% saturated water. The TDS of salt water is about 32,000 ppm.
Your tap water TDS is about 500 ppm.
No magic, pressure and semi permeable membranes in properly designed enclosures.
